{"title_page": "Jack Rose (colonel)", "text_new": "{{Short description|South African analytical chemist (1876-1973)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   = \n | name               = Jack Rose\n | honorific_suffix   = \n | image              = \n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = \n | office             = President of [[Southern Africa Association for the Advancement of Science|South African Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n | term_start         = 1943\n | term_end           = 1944\n | deputy             = \n | predecessor        = Pijper, A.\n| successor          =Chubb, E.C.\n | order2              = \n | office2             = Grand Master of Lodge de Goede Hoop ([[Freemasonry in South Africa|South African Freemasons]])\n | term_start2         = 1944\n | term_end2           = 1957\n | predecessor2        = Silberbauer, C.C.\n | successor2          = [[Colin Graham Botha|Botha, C.G.]] \n | birth_name      = John George Rose\n | birth_date      =   11 January 1876\n | birth_place     = [[Cape Town]],  [[Cape Colony]],  South Africa\n | death_date      = 1973\n| death_place     = Cape Town, [[Cape Province]] ,  South Africa\n\n | nationality     = South African\n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | spouse          = \n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | mother          =  \n | father          =  \n | residence       = \n | education       = \n | alma_mater      = \n | known_for       = Analytical chemistry, military career and Freemasonry\n | awards          = \n | committees      = \n | portfolio       = \n | blank1          = \n | data1           = \n | blank2          = \n | data2           = \n | blank3          = \n | data3           = \n | blank4          = \n | data4           = \n | blank5          = \n | data5           = \n | signature       = \n | signature_alt   = \n | website         = \n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n | module          = \n | module2         = \n | footnotes       = \n}}\n'''John George Rose''' (1876\u20131973) was a South African analytical chemist, an officer in various wars and a Grand Master of the Freemasons of South Africa.\n\n==Roots==\nRose was born on 11 January 1876 in Cape Town,  South Africa. He was the son of John Edwin Benjamin Rose (auditor-general of the Cape Colony) and Emmerentia Johanna Steytler. He died in Cape Town in a house called Beau Soliel in 1973 at 97 years old. Today the house is the Beau Soliel Music Centre.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beausoleil.org.za|title= Beau Soliel Music Centre }}</ref> He attended the South African College School in Cape Town and passed matric at the University of the Cape of Good Hope in 1893.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofsouthaf00ritc_0/page/n5|title= The history of the South African College, 1829-1918.|publisher= T. Maskew Miller|date= 1918 |author= Ritchie, W.}}</ref>\n\n==Career as a chemist==\n<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.s2a3.org.za/bio/Biograph_final.php?serial=2394|title=Biography}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 1896, he started to work as assistant analyst in the Government Analytical Laboratory, Cape Town.  In 1912 the Government appoint him as a first-grade chemical assistant in the Government Analytical Laboratory. The  [[South African Railways and Harbours Administration]] appointed him as chief chemist in 1929. He stayed in that position until his retirement in 1935. He was an analytical chemist by trade.\n\n==Membership and contributions in the chemical field==\nRose was a member of various science and chemical organizations or associations and published articles:\n*1903 \u2013 Membership of the [[Southern Africa Association for the Advancement of Science|South African Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n*1905 \u2013 Membership of the [[British Science Association|British Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n*1910 \u2013 Membership [[Royal Society of South Africa]]\n*1910 \u2013 Published papers:\n**The Insizwa copper-nickel deposits<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.mindat.org/loc-244671.html|title=references}}</ref>\n**A new Cape thermal chalybeate spring <ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.scielo.org.za/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S1816-79502008000200004 |title=References|journal=Water SA|volume=34|issue=2|pages=163\u2013174|date=2008|last1=Van Der Walt|first1=I. J.|last2=Van Niekerk|first2=H. J.|last3=Olivier|first3=J.}}</ref>\n*1921 \u2013 Membership of the South African Association of Analytical Chemists<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saci.co.za/pdf/SACI%20History%201912%20-%201962.pdf| title=History}}</ref>\n*1923 \u2013 President of Cape Chemical Society\n*1929 \u2013 Published paper:   \u2013 Alcohol mixtures as motor fuel in South Africa\n*1933 \u2013 Membership Institute of Chemistry of Great Britain and Ireland<ref>{{Cite journal |title= Institute of Chemistry of Great Britain and Ireland|journal= Proceedings of the Institute of Chemistry of Great Britain and Ireland|volume= 10|pages= A001|doi= 10.1039/PG886100A001|year= 1886}}</ref>\n*1943 \u2013 President of South African Association for the Advancement of Science\n\n==Sport==\n\n*1899 \u2013 World record holder for one-hour cycling. He did just under 48&nbsp;km in the hour.<ref>{{Cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=hQ9bDwAAQBAJ&dq=jack+rose+cycle+record+1899|title= The Cape Town Book: A Guide to the City's History, People and Places |author=Brodie, N.|publisher= Penguin Random House South Africa|date= 2015 |isbn=9781920545994}}</ref>\n\n==Military==\n\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://samilitaryhistory.org/12/c12julne.html|title=South African military History Society}}</ref>\nRose had a long military career, stretching over two World Wars:\n* Served in the South African College Cadet Corps for five years, later becoming the corps commander.\n* In the Anglo-Boer War between 1899 and 1902, he was a captain in the Cape Colonial Cycle Corps. In this war he received the [[Queen's South Africa Medal|Queen\u2019s medal.]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.defence.gov.au/Medals/Imperial/Boer/Queens-South-Africa-Medal.asp|title= Queen's South Africa Medal|accessdate=30 October 2018|date= 2013-09-26}}</ref>\n* Rose then served as lieutenant in the [[Cape Town Rifles|Duke of Edinburgh's Own Volunteer Rifles]]\n* In World War I he was assigned to the mechanical transport in the [[South West Africa campaign|German South West Africa project]]. He received the Star medal <ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.defence.gov.au/Medals/Imperial/WWI/1914-15-Star.asp|title=1914-15 Star|accessdate=22 October 2018|date=2013-09-26}}</ref> and [[Croix de Guerre | Croix de Guerre medal]]. He obtained the rank of lieutenant-colonel and later became the chief inspector of mechanical transport in [[East African Campaign (World War I)|East Africa]]. He also received the [[Distinguished Service Order |Distinguished Service Order (DSO) medal]].\n* World War II broke out and Rose was director of transportation of the [[Union Defence Force (South Africa)|Union Defence Force]].\n\n==Freemasons==\n\nHe was a Grand Master of the Freemasons in South Africa from 1944 to 1957, after he took over from Conrad Silberbauer. [[Colin Graham Botha|Colonel C.G. Botha]] took over from him in 1957.<ref>The effects of political , economic and social events on the order of Freemasons in South Africa, with reference to the movement for the formation of a united grand lodge 1772-1961 by Cooper, A.A.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grandlodge.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/The-Square-and-Compasses-No-54-July-2016.pdf|title= M W Bros John Rose and Graham Botha}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://freemasonrysd.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=551%3Athe-deputy-grand-masters-of-the-netherlands&catid=46%3Aover-200-years-of-history&Itemid=66|title= Deputy Grand Masters of the Netherlands|access-date= 2018-10-30|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180925143643/http://www.freemasonrysd.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=551%3Athe-deputy-grand-masters-of-the-netherlands&catid=46%3Aover-200-years-of-history&Itemid=66|archive-date= 2018-09-25|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:South African Freemasons]]\n[[Category:South African military personnel]]\n[[Category:South African chemists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|South African analytical chemist (1876-1973)}}\n{{Infobox mayor\n | honorific_prefix   = \n | name               = Jack Rose\n | honorific_suffix   = \n | image              = \n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = \n | office             = President of [[Southern Africa Association for the Advancement of Science |South African Association for the Advancement of Science ]]\n | term_start         = 1943\n | term_end           = 1944\n | deputy             = \n | predecessor        = Pijper, A.\n| successor          =Chubb, E.C.\n | order2              = \n | office2             = Grand Master of Lodge de Goede Hoop ([[Freemasonry in South Africa |South African Freemasons]])\n | term_start2         = 1944\n | term_end2           = 1957\n | predecessor2        = Silberbauer, C.C.\n | successor2          = [[Colin Graham Botha| Botha, C.G.]] \n | birth_name      = John George Rose\n | birth_date      =   11 January 1876\n | birth_place     = [[Cape Town]],  [[Cape Colony]],  South Africa\n | death_date      = 1973\n| death_place     = Cape Town, [[Cape Province]] ,  South Africa\n\n | nationality     = South African\n | otherparty      =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n | spouse          = \n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | mother          =  \n | father          =  \n | residence       = \n | education       = \n | alma_mater      = \n | known_for       = Analytical chemistry, military career and Freemasonry\n | awards          = \n | committees      = \n | portfolio       = \n | blank1          = \n | data1           = \n | blank2          = \n | data2           = \n | blank3          = \n | data3           = \n | blank4          = \n | data4           = \n | blank5          = \n | data5           = \n | signature       = \n | signature_alt   = \n | website         = \n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n | module          = \n | module2         = \n | footnotes       = \n}}\n'''John George Rose''' (1876\u20131973) was a South African analytical chemist, an officer in various wars and a Grand Master of the Freemasons of South Africa.\n\n==Roots==\nRose was born on 11 January 1876 in Cape Town,  South Africa. He was the son of John Edwin Benjamin Rose (auditor-general of the Cape Colony) and Emmerentia Johanna Steytler. He died in Cape Town in a house called Beau Soliel in 1973 at 97 years old. Today the house is the Beau Soliel Music Centre.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beausoleil.org.za|title= Beau Soliel Music Centre }}</ref>. He attended the South African College School in Cape Town and passed matric at the University of the Cape of Good Hope in 1893.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofsouthaf00ritc_0/page/n5|title= The history of the South African College, 1829-1918.|publisher= T. Maskew Miller|date= 1918 |author= Ritchie, W.}}</ref>\n\n==Career as a chemist== \n<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.s2a3.org.za/bio/Biograph_final.php?serial=2394|title=Biography}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 1896, he started to work as assistant analyst in the Government Analytical Laboratory, Cape Town.  In 1912 the Government appoint him as a first-grade chemical assistant in the Government Analytical Laboratory. The  [[South African Railways and Harbours Administration]] appointed him as chief chemist in 1929. He stayed in that position until his retirement in 1935. He was an analytical chemist by trade.\n\n==Membership and contributions in the chemical field==\nRose was a member of various science and chemical organizations or associations and published articles:\n*1903 \u2013 Membership of the [[Southern Africa Association for the Advancement of Science |South African Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n*1905 \u2013 Membership of the [[British Science Association|British Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n*1910 \u2013 Membership [[Royal Society of South Africa]]\n*1910 \u2013 Published papers:\n**The Insizwa copper-nickel deposits<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.mindat.org/loc-244671.html|title=references}}</ref>\n**A new Cape thermal chalybeate spring <ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.scielo.org.za/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S1816-79502008000200004 |title=References|journal=Water SA|volume=34|issue=2|pages=163\u2013174|date=2008|last1=Van Der Walt|first1=I. J.|last2=Van Niekerk|first2=H. J.|last3=Olivier|first3=J.}}</ref>\n*1921 \u2013 Membership of the South African Association of Analytical Chemists<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saci.co.za/pdf/SACI%20History%201912%20-%201962.pdf| title=History}}</ref>\n*1923 \u2013 President of Cape Chemical Society\n*1929 \u2013 Published paper:   \u2013 Alcohol mixtures as motor fuel in South Africa\n*1933 \u2013 Membership Institute of Chemistry of Great Britain and Ireland<ref>{{Cite journal |title= Institute of Chemistry of Great Britain and Ireland|journal= Proceedings of the Institute of Chemistry of Great Britain and Ireland|volume= 10|pages= A001|doi= 10.1039/PG886100A001|year= 1886}}</ref>\n*1943 \u2013 President of South African Association for the Advancement of Science\n\n==Sport==\n\n*1899 \u2013 World record holder for one-hour cycling. He did just under 48&nbsp;km in the hour.<ref>{{Cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=hQ9bDwAAQBAJ&dq=jack+rose+cycle+record+1899|title= The Cape Town Book: A Guide to the City's History, People and Places |author=Brodie, N.|publisher= Penguin Random House South Africa|date= 2015 |isbn=9781920545994}}</ref>\n==Military==\n\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://samilitaryhistory.org/12/c12julne.html|title=South African military History Society}}</ref>\nRose had a long military career, stretching over two World Wars:\n* Served in the South African College Cadet Corps for five years, later becoming the corps commander.\n* In the Anglo-Boer War between 1899 and 1902, he was a captain in the Cape Colonial Cycle Corps. In this war he received the [[Queen's South Africa Medal | Queen\u2019s medal.]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.defence.gov.au/Medals/Imperial/Boer/Queens-South-Africa-Medal.asp|title= Queen's South Africa Medal|accessdate=30 October 2018|date= 2013-09-26}}</ref>\n* Rose then served as lieutenant in the[[ Cape Town Rifles | Duke of Edinburgh's Own Volunteer Rifles]]\n* In World War I he was assigned to the mechanical transport in the [[South West Africa campaign| German South West Africa project]]. He received the Star medal <ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.defence.gov.au/Medals/Imperial/WWI/1914-15-Star.asp|title=1914-15 Star|accessdate=22 October 2018|date=2013-09-26}}</ref> and [[Croix de Guerre | Croix de Guerre medal]]. He obtained the rank of lieutenant-colonel and later became the chief inspector of mechanical transport in [[East African Campaign (World War I)| East Africa]]. He also received the [[Distinguished Service Order |Distinguished Service Order (DSO) medal]].\n* World War II broke out and Rose was director of transportation of the [[Union Defence Force (South Africa)| Union Defence Force]].\n\n==Freemasons==\n\nHe was a Grand Master of the Freemasons in South Africa from 1944 to 1957, after he took over from Conrad Silberbauer. [[Colin Graham Botha| Colonel C.G. Botha]] took over from him in 1957. <ref>The effects of political , economic and social events on the order of Freemasons in South Africa, with reference to the movement for the formation of a united grand lodge 1772-1961 by Cooper, A.A.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grandlodge.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/The-Square-and-Compasses-No-54-July-2016.pdf|title= M W Bros John Rose and Graham Botha}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://freemasonrysd.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=551%3Athe-deputy-grand-masters-of-the-netherlands&catid=46%3Aover-200-years-of-history&Itemid=66|title= Deputy Grand Masters of the Netherlands|access-date= 2018-10-30|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180925143643/http://www.freemasonrysd.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=551%3Athe-deputy-grand-masters-of-the-netherlands&catid=46%3Aover-200-years-of-history&Itemid=66|archive-date= 2018-09-25|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:South African Freemasons]]\n[[Category:South African military personnel]]\n[[Category:South African chemists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Rose_(colonel)"}
{"title_page": "Greenwich Town Hall, London", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n| name =Greenwich Town Hall\n| native_name =\n| image =Meridian House (Former Greenwich Town Hall).jpg\n| caption =Greenwich Town Hall\n| locmapin =Greater London\n| map_caption =Shown in Greater London\n| coordinates = {{coord |51.4783|N|0.01328|W|type:landmark_region:GB-WFT|display=inline,title}}\n| location =[[Greenwich]]\n| area =\n| built =1939\n| architect = Clifford Culpin\n| architecture =[[Art Deco]] style\n| governing_body =\n| designation1 =Grade II Listed Building\n| designation1_offname =\n| designation1_date =13 November 1990\n| designation1_number =1213855\n| website=\n}}\n'''Greenwich Town hall''' is a municipal building in [[Greenwich]], London. It is a Grade II [[listed building]].<ref name=nhle>{{NHLE|desc=The Borough Hall and Meridian House (former Greenwich Town Hall)|num=1213855|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:West Greenwich Community Centre - geograph.org.uk - 1464283.jpg|thumb|left|The old town hall in Greenwich High Road]]\nThe building was commissioned to replace the old town hall in Greenwich High Road which had served as the headquarters for the [[Greenwich District Board of Works]] before becoming the home of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Greenwich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greenwichwest.org.uk/about|title=About us|publisher=Greenwich West|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe site chosen for the new building had previously been occupied by the old [[Greenwich Theatre]].<ref>''The Era'' 29 May 1864, p 10 New Greenwich Theatre</ref> The new building, which was designed by  Clifford Culpin in the [[Art Deco]] style, was completed in 1939.<ref name=nhle/> It shows the influence of [[Hilversum]] town hall in the Netherlands.<ref name=nhle/> The south east wing of the building, known as the Borough Hall, contained the council chamber.<ref name=nhle/>\n\nThe building was the headquarters of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Greenwich]] until the borough was merged with the [[Metropolitan Borough of Woolwich]] to form the [[Royal Borough of Greenwich|London Borough of Greenwich]] with its new headquarters at [[Woolwich Town Hall]] in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1963/33/contents|title=Local Government Act 1963|publisher=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the town hall ceased to be the local seat of government, it was extensively altered to create floors in the area of the council chamber in 1974.<ref name=nhle/> Renamed Meridian House, to reflect the fact that the [[prime meridian]] goes through Greenwich,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manchesterhistory.net/architecture/1930/greenwichTH.html|title=Greenwich Town Hall|publisher=Manchester History|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> it became the home of [[GSM London]] at that time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808132535/http://www.gsmlondon.ac.uk/about-gsm-london|title=About GSM London|publisher=GSM London|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the Borough Hall was used as a concert venue: the band [[Squeeze (band)|Squeeze]] gave their first performance there in 1975,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londonremembers.com/memorials/squeeze-debut-gig|title=Squeeze debut gig|website=London Remembers|language=en|access-date=2017-05-23}}</ref> as commemorated by a [[blue plaque]] on the side of the building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prsformusic.com/press/2010/prs-for-music-honours-squeezes-first-gig|title=PRS for Music honours Squeeze's first gig|website=prsformusic.com|language=en|access-date=2017-05-23}}</ref> The Borough Hall went on to become the home of [[Greenwich Dance]] from 1993<ref name=first10>{{Cite news|url=http://londondance.com/articles/features/greenwich-dance-agency-the-first-10-years/|title=Greenwich Dance Agency - the first 10 years - LondonDance|work=LondonDance|access-date=2017-05-23|language=en}}</ref> until the organisation moved out in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://853london.com/2018/04/13/borough-halls-to-remain-arts-venue-despite-greenwich-dance-departure-council-says/|title=Borough Halls to remain arts venue despite Greenwich Dance departure, council says|last=Chamberlain|first=Darryl|date=2018-04-13|website=853|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government buildings completed in 1939]]\n[[Category:City and town halls in London]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in the Royal Borough of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed government buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n| name =Greenwich Town Hall\n| native_name =\n| image =Meridian House (Former Greenwich Town Hall).jpg\n| caption =Greenwich Town Hall\n| locmapin =Greater London\n| map_caption =Shown in Greater London\n| coordinates = {{coord |51.4783|N|0.01328|W|type:landmark_region:GB-WFT|display=inline,title}}\n| location =[[Greenwich]]\n| area =\n| built =1939\n| architect = Clifford Culpin\n| architecture =[[Art Deco]] style\n| governing_body =\n| designation1 =Grade II Listed Building\n| designation1_offname =\n| designation1_date =13 November 1990\n| designation1_number =1213855\n| website=\n}}\n'''Greenwich Town hall''' is a municipal building in [[Greenwich]], London. It is a Grade II [[listed building]].<ref name=nhle>{{NHLE|desc=The Borough Hall and Meridian House (former Greenwich Town Hall)|num=1213855|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:West Greenwich Community Centre - geograph.org.uk - 1464283.jpg|thumb|left|The old town hall in Greenwich High Road]]\nThe building was commissioned to replace the old town hall in Greenwich High Road which had served as the headquarters for the [[Greenwich District Board of Works]] before becoming the home of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Greenwich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greenwichwest.org.uk/about|title=About us|publisher=Greenwich West|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe site chosen for the new building had previously been occupied by the old [[Greenwich Theatre]].<ref>''The Era'' 29 May 1864, p 10 New Greenwich Theatre</ref> The new building, which was designed by  Clifford Culpin in the [[Art Deco]] style was completed in 1939.<ref name=nhle/> It shows the influence of [[Hilversum]] town hall in the Netherlands.<ref name=nhle/> The south east wing of the building, known as the Borough Hall, contained the council chamber.<ref name=nhle/>\n\nThe building was the headquarters of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Greenwich]] until the borough was merged with the [[Metropolitan Borough of Woolwich]] to form the [[Royal Borough of Greenwich|London Borough of Greenwich]] with its new headquarters at [[Woolwich Town Hall]] in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1963/33/contents|title=Local Government Act 1963|publisher=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the town hall ceased to be the local seat of government, it was extensively altered to create floors in the area of the council chamber in 1974.<ref name=nhle/> Renamed Meridian House, to reflect the fact that the [[prime meridian]] goes through Greenwich,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manchesterhistory.net/architecture/1930/greenwichTH.html|title=Greenwich Town Hall|publisher=Manchester History|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> it became the home of [[GSM London]] at that time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808132535/http://www.gsmlondon.ac.uk/about-gsm-london|title=About GSM London|publisher=GSM London|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the Borough Hall was used as a concert venue: the band [[Squeeze (band)|Squeeze]] gave their first performance there in 1975,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londonremembers.com/memorials/squeeze-debut-gig|title=Squeeze debut gig|website=London Remembers|language=en|access-date=2017-05-23}}</ref> as commemorated by a [[blue plaque]] on the side of the building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prsformusic.com/press/2010/prs-for-music-honours-squeezes-first-gig|title=PRS for Music honours Squeeze's first gig|website=prsformusic.com|language=en|access-date=2017-05-23}}</ref> The Borough Hall went on to become the home of [[Greenwich Dance]] from 1993<ref name=first10>{{Cite news|url=http://londondance.com/articles/features/greenwich-dance-agency-the-first-10-years/|title=Greenwich Dance Agency - the first 10 years - LondonDance|work=LondonDance|access-date=2017-05-23|language=en}}</ref> until the organisation moved out in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://853london.com/2018/04/13/borough-halls-to-remain-arts-venue-despite-greenwich-dance-departure-council-says/|title=Borough Halls to remain arts venue despite Greenwich Dance departure, council says|last=Chamberlain|first=Darryl|date=2018-04-13|website=853|language=en|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government buildings completed in 1939]]\n[[Category:City and town halls in London]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in the Royal Borough of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed government buildings]]\n", "name_user": "Paul W", "label": "safe", "comment": "comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greenwich_Town_Hall,_London"}
{"title_page": "Poppin", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 single by KSI featuring Lil Pump and Smokepurpp}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Poppin\n| cover      = KSI Poppin Cover.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]] featuring [[Lil Pump]] and [[Smokepurpp]]\n| album      = Dissimulation\n| released   = 27 March 2020\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   = 2020\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 3:33\n| label      =\n* [[RBC Records|RBC]]\n* [[BMG Rights Management|BMG]]\n| writer     =\n* [[KSI (entertainer)|Olajide Olatunji]]\n* [[Lil Pump|Gazzy Garcia]]\n* [[Smokepurpp|Omar Pineiro]]\n* Diego Avendano\n* Kevin Price\n* Jamal Rashid<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |title=Poppin by KSI featuring Lil Pump & Smokepurpp |url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/133831942/credits |website=Tidal |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n| producer   =\n* Diego Ave\n* Go Grizzly\n* Mally Mall<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n| chronology = [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]]\n| prev_title = [[Wake Up Call (KSI song)|Wake Up Call]]\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| next_title = [[Houdini (KSI song)|Houdini]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Lil Pump]]\n | type       = Singles\n | prev_title = You Know You Lit\n | prev_year  = 2020\n | title      = Poppin\n | year       = 2020\n | next_title = Illuminati\n | next_year  = 2020\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Smokepurpp]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = RR\n | prev_year  = 2020\n | title      = Poppin\n | year       = 2020\n | next_title = \n | next_year  = \n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|xa0qshcRhDQ|\"Down Like That\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Poppin'''\" is a song by British YouTube personality and rapper [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]], featuring American rappers [[Lil Pump]] and [[Smokepurpp]]. The song is produced by American producers Diego Ave, Go Grizzly and Mally Mall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ksi-unites-with-lil-pump-and-smokepurpp-on-gaudy-poppin-new-song.1986685.html|title=KSI Unites With Lil Pump & Smokepurpp On Gaudy \"Poppin\"|website=HotNewHipHop|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> It was released on 27 March 2020 through [[RBC Records]], under [[BMG Rights Management]].<ref name=\"ein2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.einnews.com/pr_news/512477940/ksi-to-release-new-single-poppin-featuring-lil-pump-smokepurpp-on-march-27th|title=KSI to Release New Single, \u201cPoppin\u201d Featuring Lil Pump, Smokepurpp on March 27th|date=23 March 2020|publisher=EIN News}}</ref> It is the third single from KSI's upcoming 2020 debut album ''Dissimulation''. The song charted at number 43 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20200403/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 {{!}} Official Charts Company|last=|first=|date=|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Promotion ==\nOn 18 March 2020, KSI announced via social media that he would be releasing a new single in the next week, and on the same day, he posted the song's artwork to his social media pages, revealing that the song is titled \"Poppin\" and that it features Lil Pump and Smokepurpp.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=KSIOlajidebt|number=1240310548371255297|title=New single coming out next week. Clue of the song name and feature here https://K-S-I.lnk.to/search/spotify|date=2020-03-18|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=KSIOlajidebt|number=1240344439651995654|title=https://ksi.ffm.to/poppin\u00a0 Out next week lmao. Pre order/pre save nowpic.twitter.com/ZjO6pXx2ZG|date=2020-03-18|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B94plYrAFBM/|title=KSI on Instagram: \u201cPopping ft @lilpump and @smokepurpp Link in bio\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> The song was made available for [[pre-order]] on the same day.<ref name=\"ein2\"/>\n\n=== \"Poppin challenge\" ===\nOn 30 March 2020, KSI announced via social media that he would be hosting a competition called \"#PoppinChallenge\". He asked people to record and submit their own verses for \"Poppin\", and the best verse, decided by public vote, will replace Lil Pump's verse on a remix of the song which will appear on the deluxe edition of KSI's upcoming 2020 album ''Dissimulation''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/KSIOlajidebt/status/1244735326179950593|title=Got a big one for you  #poppinchallengepic.twitter.com/NWe2Lq74Gq|last=KSI|date=2020-03-30|website=@KSIOlajidebt|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> On 17 April 2020, American YouTube rapper Crypt was announced as the winner of the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oMIRi2eTgb0|title=The Winner Of The Poppin Challenge Is...|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QOCY2QC7AWY|title=I WON THE KSI POPPIN' CHALLENGE|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/ksi-new-rap-music-poppin-youtuber-boxing-jake-logan-paul-2020-4|title=KSI conquered YouTube and boxing. Now, he wants to break the mold of 'YouTuber music,' and blow 'trash' musicians like the Paul brothers out of the water.|last=Tenbarge|first=Kat|website=Insider|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nThe song entered the UK Singles Chart at number 43.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48106/ksi/|title=KSI {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> It dropped to number 56 the following week, before dropping out of the top 100.<ref name=\":1\" /> The song spent two weeks on the [[UK R&B Singles and Albums Charts|UK R&B Singles Chart]], peaking at number 23.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/r-and-b-singles-chart/20200410/114/|title=Official R&B Singles Chart Top 40 {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\nAn audio visualiser video for the song was uploaded to KSI's [[YouTube]] channel on 26 March 2020. As of April 2020, it has 6 million views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GGLE8gk9fng|title=KSI - Poppin (feat. Lil Pump & Smokepurpp)|date=26 March 2020|via=[[YouTube]]|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The music video, directed by TajvsJaj, was filmed in [[Los Angeles]] in March 2020 and was uploaded to KSI's YouTube channel on 3 April 2020, one week after the release of the song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ksi-poppin-lil-pump-smokepurpp|title=KSI Gives Visual Treatment To \"Poppin\" Featuring Lil Pump & Smokepurpp|last=|first=|date=3 April 2020|website=[[GRM Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The music video stars Asian dancer Bailey Sok and features cameo appearances from American actor and comedian [[King Bach]] and two of the song's producers, Diego Ave and Mally Mall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grungecake.com/ksi-popping-lil-pump-smokepurpp/articles/65556|title=English rapper KSI enlists Lil Pump and Smokepurpp for 'Poppin': Watch|date=2020-04-06|website=GRUNGECAKE|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> As of April 2020, it has 7 million views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xa0qshcRhDQ|title=KSI - Poppin (feat. Lil Pump & Smokepurpp) [Official Music Video]|last=|first=|date=3 April 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> A [[Making-of|behind-the-scenes]] video of the filming of the music video was uploaded to KSI's YouTube channel on 10 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fmf_KsHjGC8|title=KSI - Poppin (feat. Lil Pump & Smokepurpp) [Behind The Scenes]|last=|first=|date=10 April 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital download<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n| title1 = Poppin\n| note1 = featuring [[Lil Pump]] and [[Smokepurpp]]\n| length1 = 3:33\n| length6 = \n| length10 = \n| title10 = \n| length9 = \n| title9 = \n| length8 = \n| title8 = \n| length7 = \n| title7 = \n| length5 = \n| title6 = \n| title5 = \n| length4 = \n| title4 = \n| length3 = \n| title3 = \n| length2 = \n| title2 = \n| all_writing = \n| total_length = \n}}\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n{{div col}}\n*[[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]] \u2013 vocals, songwriter\n*[[Lil Pump]] \u2013 vocals, songwriter\n*[[Smokepurpp]] \u2013 vocals, songwriter\n*Diego Ave \u2013 producer, songwriter\n*Go Grizzly \u2013 producer, songwriter\n*Mally Mall \u2013 producer, songwriter\n*Henkka Niemist\u00f6 \u2013 engineer\n*Michalis Michael \u2013 engineer\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Chart (2020)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 52\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | New Zealand Hot Singles ([[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4841|title=NZ Hot Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=4 