{"title_page": "Battle of Carrhae (296)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Carrhae (296)\n| partof      = the [[Roman\u2013Persian Wars]]\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| date        = 296 or 297 CE<ref name=\"Frye (1993), 130; Southern (2001), 242\"/>\n| place       = Between [[Harran|Carrhae]] and [[Callinicum]], (present day [[Turkey]])\n| casus       = \n| territory   = \n| result      = Decisive [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] victory<ref>[https://books.google.fr/books?id=OIzreCGlHxIC&pg=PT465&lpg=PT465&dq=roman+persian+war+421-422&source=bl&ots=zPOfJBDiON&sig=lFMhwjb6j8RmZE4SPj410H0UN9g&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj2nfukzKbaAhWSblAKHXNpDmwQ6AEIZzAF#v=onepage&q=roman%20persian%20war%20421-422&f=false/ Dictionary of Wars] \"The Roman Caesar for the east, Galerius (d. 311), and a relatively small army marched against the Persians, won some minor victories in Mesopotamia, but were decisively routed at the battle of Carrhea (Harran) in 296.\"</ref><ref>[https://books.google.fr/books?id=MNSyT_PuYVMC&pg=PA468&lpg=PA468&dq=siege+of+nisibis+252+sassanian+victory&source=bl&ots=uMv7i1QkdU&sig=kCsvdz0Ol7JGaIaTOyd9ntlL36A&hl=fr&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=siege%20of%20nisibis%20252%20sassanian%20victory&f=false/ The Cambridge Ancient History: Volume 12, The Crisis of Empire, AD 193-337]\"Since Diocletian was occupied in Egypt, he sent his Caesar Galerius against Narseh who met the Romans and defeated them somewhere in upper Mesopotamia\"</ref>\n| combatant1  = [[Sassanid Empire]]\n| combatant2  = [[Roman Empire]]\n| commander1  = [[Narseh]]\n| commander2  = [[Galerius]]<br>Tiridates\n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = Unknown\n| casualties2 = Heavy\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Roman-Persian Wars}}\nThe '''Battle of Carrhae''' or the '''Battle of Callinicum''' took place in 296 or 297,<ref name=\"Frye (1993), 130; Southern (2001), 242\">Frye (1993), 130; Southern (2001), 242</ref> after the invasion of [[Mesopotamia]] and [[Kingdom of Armenia (antiquity)|Armenia]] by the [[Sasanian]] king [[Narseh]]. The battle took place between Carrhae and Callinicum and was a decisive victory for the Sasanians. \n\nGalerius and Tiridates escaped with a remnant of Roman forces to [[Antioch]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dupuy |first1=Richard Ernest |title=The Harper Encyclopedia of Military History: From 3500 BC to the Present |date=1993 |publisher=HarperCollins |isbn=978-0-06-270056-8 |page=175a |language=en}}</ref> Eutropius and Theophanes have recorded versions of a celebrated story regarding a public humiliation of Galerius by Diolectan.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Edwards |first1=Iorwerth Eiddon Stephen |last2=Gadd |first2=Cyril John |last3=Hammond |first3=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re |last4=Boardman |first4=John |last5=Walbank |first5=Frank William |last6=Lewis |first6=David Malcolm |last7=Bowman |first7=Alan |last8=Astin |first8=A. E. |last9=Garnsey |first9=Peter |last10=Crook |first10=John Anthony |last11=Lintott |first11=Andrew William |last12=Cameron |first12=Averil |last13=Rawson |first13=Elizabeth |last14=Champlin |first14=Edward |last15=Rathbone |first15=Dominic |last16=Ward-Perkins |first16=Bryan |last17=Whitby |first17=Michael |title=The Cambridge Ancient History: Volume 12, The Crisis of Empire, AD 193-337 |date=1970 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-30199-2 |page=81 |language=en}}</ref> was trying to distance himselffrom the stigma of this defeat.\n\nDiolectan later sent reinforcements for Galerius, and the latter managed to defeat the [[Sassanids]] two years later at the [[Battle of Satala (298)]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Battles involving the Roman Empire|Carrhae]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Sasanian Empire|Carrhae]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Roman\u2013Sasanian Wars|Carrhae 296]]\n[[Category:290s conflicts|Carrhae 296]]\n[[Category:296]]\n[[Category:History of \u015eanl\u0131urfa Province]]\n[[Category:3rd century in Iran]]\n[[Category:290s in the 